div.div:
When system needs to find the way from point X to C, it will find from
A to C and from B to C and add to them i and j, respectively. Other
times, system may need to find the way from X to Y. The logic is very
similar. The system will find the way from A to C and B to E, and add
to them i and i', and j and j' i.e. distances from X to A and B, and from
Y to C and E. And the more complex example is with cross segments
the system will have to calculate the distance from X to each of the
exit/entry point for the segment E1 and E2. Note exit/entry points of
segment S1 are different points from point E on the drawing.

div.font:
Road Classifier can determine if this is a one lane, two, or six
lanes road. And, it sends this info as a message to KAFKA.
Road Classifier can detect if there are STOPs, red lights, etc.
based on how the traffic is going e.g. cars are stopping and
after some time continue. Similarly, it can determine is it a bus
(having frequent stops at given points), a 2 wheeler (motor,
speeds up more than cars and breaks sharply), a 4 wheeler.

div.font:
New Roads Job can determine if this is a new road and send
a message to KAFKA, whichMap Update Service will pick up
and update the map to include the new road and save it in the
database. Each time a new road is found Map Update Service
will call Graph Processing Service and tell I found a new road
isfound, please store it in the database.
Avg Speed Job will figure out with what average speed users
are moving on a given part of the road and will send this info
to KAFKA. Traffic Update Service will pick up the message
and update the weights of the graph through Graph Processing
Service.

nicate back to the driver, the system can use WebSocket Handler. It asks WebSockets Manager for the user-connected websocket (cached in Redis) and sends the message.

div.div:
Maps service is a light-weight service, it offers interfaces to different clients. It forwards the requests to the Graph Processing Service does a lot of things. First it queries
Segment Service, which sits on the top of Cassandra and reads all the segments. If the two points falls within the same segment, the Graph Processing Service may want
to check does it have the route cached and if so to return it to the device. If it does not have it, it may run Dijkstra algorithm. If two points are in different segments, Graph
Processing Service will use the segment information to calculate the route.
